Thank you, law enforcement community, for your excellent, tireless work this week and going forward. I am completely confident that justice will be done.

Now, as a community, we can trust them to do their part while we play ours - to grieve, heal, and grow together as Utahns.

The violence from this week affects all of us in a lot of different ways. People are hurting and uncertain. 

We have an opportunity to invoke the best parts of ourselves and heal together, stronger, like Utahns have always done. Call your friends and neighbors who are hurting. Let's help each other work through the ugly feelings without being ugly to each other. Let’s rise to this occasion together.

After yesterday’s tragic events, I want to speak directly to Utahns—and especially to our young people. My message is below.

Never Forget.

6/ This ruling is about more than road repair—it’s about access, control, and good partnerships between federal land managers and locals.
5/ This week, local governments won. The ruling reaffirms local control, clears the way for needed improvements, and ensures Utahns can continue to access and enjoy the lands they love.
3/ Many of these roads have become public safety concerns due to overuse and disrepair. The counties weren’t allowed to fix them, complicating search and rescue operations.
2/ The federal government has been in litigation with the state and counties for decades —because control of roads = control of access and wilderness eligibility.

1/ These are R.S. 2477 roads—a law from 1866 that let states and counties build and maintain roads across public lands to develop the West. Though repealed in 1976, existing roads remained locally controlled. However…

🚨Big win for Utah, rural counties, and public access 🚨 A federal judge just ruled that Utah, Garfield County, and Kane County legally own and manage Hole in the Rock Road and House Rock Valley Road. Here's why that matters 🧵

The Midnight Rules Relief Act will allow us to disapprove of rules issued during the last year of a President's term more efficiently. That's why I voted for this bill from @RepAndyBiggsAZ and I will continue working to hold agencies accountable and prevent federal overreach.
At the end of a President's term, there's a flurry of regulatory activity. We call it "midnight rulemaking." This makes it difficult for Congress to review each new rule.

The Constitution gives Congress power to legislate, not federal agencies. But agencies have taken on the powers of the legislative branch with no accountability. The Midnight Rules Relief Act will help us keep agencies in check.
